---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const url = 'https://systemreport.net/standards';
---
<Layout title="Editorial Standards — System Report" description="The technical and editorial standards applied to every System Report article." url={url}>
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert prose-headings:font-serif">
    <h1>Editorial Standards</h1>

    <p>Every article goes through the same automated pipeline. There are no exceptions, no expedited paths, and no human override that bypasses the gates.</p>

    <h2>Sourcing</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Articles are synthesized from at least one (usually three or more) independent feed sources covering the same event.</li>
      <li>SimHash near-duplicate collapse and cosine-embedding semantic dedup run before clustering, so visibly distinct outlets reporting the same story get merged into one article rather than three.</li>
      <li>Where the Google Search grounding pass succeeds, every published article ends with a <strong>Sources</strong> block of cited URLs.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Drafting</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Stories backed by three or more sources fan out into two parallel drafts written by different model families. A third model judges which draft to publish. This is editorial consensus by model debate.</li>
      <li>Single-source stories take the single-draft path to conserve quota.</li>
      <li>Target length is 700–900 words, three to four sections.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Quality gates</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Critique.</strong> A different-family model reviews the draft for factual issues, style problems, and missing angles. Verdict is <code>ship</code> | <code>revise</code> | <code>reject</code>. Rejected drafts are discarded.</li>
      <li><strong>Revise.</strong> Revisions address every flagged issue against the original sources.</li>
      <li><strong>Grounding.</strong> Gemini's Google Search tool fact-checks the revised draft and returns cited URLs.</li>
      <li><strong>Stylometric gate.</strong> Thirty-plus banned LLM-tell phrases (delve, game-changer, stands as a testament, etc.) trigger one more revision.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Multimodal</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Hero illustration generated by Cloudflare Workers AI Flux-1 Schnell when available, photo from Pexels as fallback.</li>
      <li>Audio narration via Groq Orpheus-v1-english TTS, served as both inline player and a podcast feed at <code>/podcast.xml</code>.</li>
      <li>An AMP Web Story version of every article at <code>/stories/&lt;slug&gt;</code>.</li>
      <li>Translations into Turkish, Spanish, French, German, Japanese, Simplified Chinese, Korean, Portuguese, Italian, and Arabic, with proper hreflang.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Reliability</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>The model router fails over across providers and models on rate limits, server errors, and quota cooldowns. No single outage stops publishing.</li>
      <li>Failed clusters are written to a dead-letter queue (<code>ops/dlq.jsonl</code>) and replayable via <code>scripts/dlq-replay.js</code>. No article is silently dropped.</li>
      <li>Chaos tests inject synthetic provider failures and assert the failover still produces output.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Open by default</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Source code is public.</li>
      <li>Article history lives in git commits — every edit is auditable.</li>
      <li>Machine-readable indexes at <code>/data/posts.json</code> and <code>/data/clusters.jsonl</code>.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
</Layout>
